[3]
Date: 22 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Singapore - Ministry of Health 22 Apr 2003 [edited]
<http://app.moh.gov.sg/sar/sar0301.asp?id=1&mid=6360>

SARS situation update 22 Apr 2003
---------------------------------
As of 22 Apr 2003, 6 additional SARS patients have been discharged,
bringing the total number of patients who have recovered from SARS to 110.
60 SARS patients remain in hospital; 19 are in intensive care.
SARS Cases
Two more SARS cases have been reported today. One is the 41 year old
daughter of the 72 year old man who was admitted as a suspected SARS case
on 19 Apr 2003 and who works in the Pasir Panjang Wholesale Market. The
other case is a 39 year old inpatient of Singapore General Hospital (SGH)
ward 57.
Update on Pasir Panjang Wholesale Market (PPWM)
To date 8 probable SARS cases have been linked to the Pasir Panjang
Wholesale Market:
Patient 1: 64 year old man who works at the PPWM. He had visited his
brother at SGH Ward 58 on 31 Mar 2003. He became unwell on 5 Apr 2003, was
admitted to the National University Hospital (NUH) on 8 Apr 2003 and died
at Tan Tock Seng Hospital (TTSH) on 12 Apr 2003 [index case from PPWM
related to SGH cluster/transmission? - Mod.MPP].
Patient 2: 54 year old taxi driver who ferried patient 1 from his home to
PPWM on 5 Apr 2003. He became unwell on 14 Apr 2003 and was admitted to
TTSH on 18 Apr 2003.
Patient 3: 45 year old man who works at PPWM. He became unwell on 8 Apr
2003 and was admitted to TTSH on 16 Apr 2003.
Patient 4: 45 year old who works at PPWM. He became unwell on 20 Apr 2003
and was admitted on 21 Apr 2003.
Patients 5-7: The 3 grandchildren (aged 4, 8, and 9 years) of a 72 year old
man who was admitted as a suspect SARS case on 19 Apr 03 and who works at
the PPWM. The 3 children became unwell on 15 and 16 Apr 2003 and were
admitted to TTSH on 19 Apr 2003.
Patient 8: 41 year old daughter of a 72 year old man who was admitted as a
suspect SARS case on 19 April 03 and who works at the PPWM.
Cases 2 to 7 are in a stable condition; patient 1 who died on 12 Apr 2003.
In addition to the 8 probable cases, 14 suspected SARS cases linked to the
market have been admitted: 8 people with direct links to the PPWM (3
workers and 5 visitors) and 6 of their family members. Among the family
members are 2 children, aged 18 months and 10 years, respectively. So far,
1204 home quarantine orders have been issued.
Kandang Kerbau Hospital Women's and Children's Hospital (KKH): a 16 month
old toddler admitted to KKH for severe asthma died on Tuesday, 15 Apr 2003.
The child died from severe asthma and lung infection, leading to acute
respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). Postmortem findings confirm that this
child died from ARDS. To date, tests for coronavirus are negative. A
specimen taken from the child's airway showed the presence of adenovirus.
Siblings of the toddler were admitted to TTSH for observation. A child who
shared a cubicle with toddler at KKH was admitted to TTSH for observation
of pneumonia. All 3 children have been discharged well from TTSH. The older
sibling of the toddler was also found to have adenovirus.
Adenovirus is not a new virus, but neither is it a common respiratory
virus. It is one of several causes of community-acquired pneumonia. People
infected with adenovirus usually have symptoms such as cough, high fever,
and red eyes. ARDS is also not new. KKH sees about 6 cases a year. The
usual causes of ARDS include viral infection, severe pneumonia, near
drowning, and aspiration pneumonia (choking). The mortality rate for ARDS
is up to 80 per cent.
Summary of SARS cases
Discharged: 110
Hospitalised: 60 (including 19 in intensive care)
Deaths: 14 + 2 (pending postmortem findings)
Total: 186
Suspected: 87 (including 5 children under 18 years)
Under home quarantine: 1798
[The identification of adenovirus infection in the infant death related to
ARDS serves as a reminder that other causes of ARDS continue to occur
during the current outbreak of SARS. This also serves as a reminder that
SARS is still a diagnosis of exclusion, after other etiologies have been
ruled out. We still do not have laboratory diagnostic tests to confirm
SARS. - Mod.MPP]
