[4]
Date: 22 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Taiwan - CDC Taiwan [edited]
<http://203.65.72.83/En/dpc/ShowPublication.ASP?RecNo=865>
Taiwan SARS update(22 Apr 2003)
-------------------------------
Premier Yu announced yesterday that beginning on 23 Apr 2003, all
passengers will be required to have their temperature checked before
departure. He reminds the public to follow the precautionary measures to
protect themselves and others from SARS infection.
[The] Department of Health, Hong Kong announced that a flight attendant who
had been on duty for the flight CX714 from Singapore to Hong Kong was
identified as a probable case of SARS. Taiwan CDC urges those who were on
the same flight to contact their local health authorities for further
evaluation.
As of 9:00 AM 22 Apr 2003, there were 196 possible SARS cases reported: 28
probable, 46 suspected, 87 excluded, and 35 pending. In accordance with WHO
guidelines, 20 of the 28 probable cases and 31 of the 46 suspected cases
have been discharged to home quarantine, while the remaining 8 probable
cases and 15 suspected cases are still being cared for in negative pressure
rooms. A total of 103 possible SARS cases have been discharged from hospitals.
Since the Taiwan SARS Advisory Committee meeting is re-scheduled to be 3
times per week, it is anticipated that the update information may be
released at the same frequency.
As of 21 Apr 2003, a total of 1909 close contacts of probable SARS cases
had been given home quarantine notifications; 1579 of them have completed
their quarantines [330 are still under quarantine - Mod.MPP].
On 21 Apr 2003, 7 passengers at CKS International Airport [Taiwan
International Airport] had fever, but they were not required [to undergo]
further evaluation. A total of 27 passengers had fever since 10 Apr 2003,
and 5 of them were reported as possible cases: 2 suspected, 2 pending, and
1 excluded.
