Date: Tue, 22 Apr 2003 14:55:25 +0430 (IRST)
From: Ali Karami <alika95@nrcgeb.ac.ir>

Concerning Dr Compton's question about survival of human coronavirus in the
environment a material safety data sheet about human coronavirus states:
Name: Human coronavirus
Section II - Health Hazard
Physical inactivation: Sensitive to heat
Survival outside host: Survives up to 24 hours on metal surfaces at ambient
conditions
Date prepared: March 2001
Prepared by: Office of Laboratory Security, PPHB
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/msds-ftss/msds83e.html>
--
Dr Ali Karami
Bagyatallah University of Medical Science
Tehran- IRAN
<alika95@nrcgeb.ac.ir>
[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Karami for this additional background information.
As Mod. CP pointed out on 21 April (in SARS - worldwide (61): cases
20030421.0977), the route of transmission of a virus will affect the
duration of survival of infectious material in the environment, and in the
case of the SARS virus, there may well be more than one route of
transmission. The SARS virus is not closely related to the 2
well-characterized human coronaviruses, which differ in stability. The SARS
virus may well differ from both of them. - Mod.MPP]
